body:
@dbarrejon thanks for the insightful comments here! Yes you are correct, there is no normalization going on here, this is simply a **rescaling** from 0 - 255 to 0.0 - 1.0.

When I first started with simple convolution networks, i.e. MNIST, I did normalization of the input images by subtracting the mean and then dividing by the standard deviation. This leaves the resultant dataset at zero mean and unity variance.

In YOLOv3 this process seems to be taken care of by the `batch_norm2d` layers. These layers carry a running mean and a running variance of the pixel values passing through them, and normalize the network values as they pass from one layer to another, not just at the input as you describe but at multiple locations throughout the network (73 locations in yolov3-spp).
